The Manhattan metric (also known as taxicab geometry, rectilinear distance, L1 distance, snake distance or city block distance) defines a distance where the length between two points (p1 and p2) is equal to the length of all paths connecting p1 and p2 along horizontal and vertical segments, without ever going back.
